# Complete AWS Serverless Deployment Guide for GitGo (Next.js 14+)

This guide walks through taking your GitGo codebase and deploying it to a scalable, production-ready AWS Serverless environment using AWS Amplify, DynamoDB, Bedrock, and MongoDB Atlas.

> **CRITICAL ARCHITECTURE NOTE:** GitGo runs in a "dual-database" mode on AWS. Some routes use DynamoDB natively, while NextAuth and User profiles use MongoDB Atlas. AI features are powered by Amazon Bedrock (Amazon Nova Pro).

---

## Step 1: Push Your Code to GitHub

AWS Amplify requires a Git repository to trigger CI/CD builds.

1. Create a private repository on [GitHub](https://github.com/new).
2. Push your local `source_code` directory to the new [main](file:///c:/Users/Shyam/OneDrive/Desktop/Python/gitgo/source_code/lib/llm.ts#593-601) branch:
   ```bash
   git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/gitgo-aws-production.git
   git branch -M main
   git push -u origin main
   ```

---

## Step 2: Set Up MongoDB Atlas (Authentication & Profiles)

GitGo uses NextAuth which requires a MongoDB connection to store user session data.

1. Go to [MongoDB Atlas](https://www.mongodb.com/cloud/atlas) and create a free shared cluster.
2. In the left sidebar, go to **Network Access**.
3. Click **Add IP Address** -> **Allow Access From Anywhere** (`0.0.0.0/0`).
    - *Why?* AWS Amplify Lambda functions change IPs constantly. Allowing all IPs is required for the SSR functions to connect to Atlas.
4. Go to **Database Access** and create a database user. Save the password.
5. Go back to **Databases** -> **Connect** -> **Drivers** and copy your Connection String (`MONGODB_URI`).

---

## Step 3: Set Up Amazon DynamoDB (Application Data)

GitGo uses DynamoDB for ultra-fast storage of cached repositories, portfolios, and analyses.

1. Open the [AWS Console](https://console.aws.amazon.com) and search for **DynamoDB**.
2. Click **Create table** and create the following 6 core tables exactly as named (case-sensitive):

| DynamoDB Table Name | Partition Key Name | Key Type |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `GitGo-Recommendations` | `userId` | String |
| `GitGo-Repositories` | `githubId` | String |
| `GitGo-ContributorFriendlyRepo` | `repoId` | Number |
| `GitGo-Portfolio` | `userId` | String |
| `GitGo-RepositoryAnalysis` | `repoId` | Number |
| `GitGo-RouteCache` | `path` | String |

---

## Step 4: Set Up Amazon S3 (Resumes)

1. In the AWS Console, search for **S3**.
2. Click **Create bucket**.
3. Name your bucket: `gitgo-resumes-bucket-users`.
4. Leave **Block all public access** CHECKED.
5. Click **Create bucket**.

---

## Step 5: Enable Amazon Bedrock (AI Models)

GitGo uses AWS Bedrock for its AI reasoning (Analyze Repo, Smart Matches). This tutorial uses **Amazon Nova Pro** as it does not require an AWS Marketplace subscription.

1. In the AWS Console, search for **Bedrock**.
2. In the left sidebar, click **Model access**.
3. Click **Manage model access** in the top right.
4. Check the box for **Amazon Nova Pro** (and Claude 3.5 Sonnet if you prefer to use that later).
5. Click **Save changes** (approval is usually instant).

---

## Step 6: Deploy to AWS Amplify

This is where the magic happens. We connect your GitHub repo to Amplify to build the Next.js frontend and SSR Lambda functions.

1. In the AWS Console, search for **AWS Amplify**.
2. Click **Create new app**.
3. Select **GitHub**, authorize it, and select your `gitgo-aws-production` repository ([main](file:///c:/Users/Shyam/OneDrive/Desktop/Python/gitgo/source_code/lib/llm.ts#593-601) branch).
| `GITHUB_TOKEN` | A personal access token starting with `ghp_...` |
| `LINKEDIN_CLIENT_ID` | Your LinkedIn Auth App Client ID |
| `LINKEDIN_CLIENT_SECRET` | Your LinkedIn Auth App Client Secret |
| `MONGODB_URI` | `mongodb+srv://...` (From Step 2) |
| `NEXTAUTH_SECRET` | A long random string (Required for production NextAuth) |
| `NEXTAUTH_URL` | `https://main.xxxxxxxx.amplifyapp.com` (Add this AFTER the first deploy finishes and you get your URL) |

6. Click Next and click **Save and deploy**.

---

## Step 7: Fix Missing IAM Permissions

While Amplify is building, you MUST give the auto-generated Amplify Role permission to talk to Bedrock, DynamoDB, and S3. If you skip this, all API routes will fail with "Access Denied 500".

1. In the Amplify Console, go to your app settings.
2. Under **App settings -> General**, locate the **Service Role** (it usually looks like `amplifyconsole-backend-role`).
3. Click the link to open IAM.
4. *Alternatively*, search IAM -> Roles -> find the `Amplify SSR Compute Role` for your app.
5. Click **Add permissions** -> **Attach policies**.
6. Search for and check the boxes for:
   - `AmazonDynamoDBFullAccess`
   - `AmazonS3FullAccess`
   - `AmazonBedrockFullAccess`
7. Click **Add permissions**.

---

## Step 8: Finalize OAuth Callbacks

Once the Amplify build is complete, you will receive your live production URL (e.g., `https://main.[YOUR_APP_ID].amplifyapp.com`).

**Update GitHub OAuth:**
1. Go to your GitHub Developer Settings -> OAuth Apps -> GitGo.
2. Change the **Homepage URL** to your new Amplify URL.
3. Change the **Authorization callback URL** to:
   `https://[YOUR_AMPLIFY_URL]/api/auth/callback/github`

**Update LinkedIn OAuth:**
1. Go to LinkedIn Developer Portal -> GitGo App -> Auth tab.
2. Add a new Redirect URL:
   `https://[YOUR_AMPLIFY_URL]/api/auth/callback/linkedin`

**Update Amplify Environment Variables:**
1. Go back to AWS Amplify -> Hosting -> Environment variables.
2. Make sure `NEXTAUTH_URL` is set to exactly your `https://[YOUR_AMPLIFY_URL]` (no trailing slash).
3. Amplify will auto-redeploy.

---

## Step 9: Launch & Test!

1. Go to your live URL.
2. **Log in with GitHub**. (This triggers the MongoDB user auto-creation script).
3. Test **My Tech Stack** -> Ensures MongoDB and GitHub syncing is working.
4. Test **Analyze Repo** -> Ensures Amazon Bedrock (Nova Pro) has correct IAM permissions and is generating responses inline.
5. Test **Smart Matches** -> Tests the 3-phase AI chain and database hydration.

If all passed, your GitGo application is successfully running in a highly available, serverless footprint on AWS!
